{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Rows with missing required fields are rejected and appear in the dead-letter queue with the original row number.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure is at a local module handoff: CSV parser/validator must pass the correct row index and payload to the DLQ writer. A unit test of only validator logic would miss row-number propagation and envelope mapping bugs (MOCK-MISS). Real OS/network/subprocess behavior is not required for this specific behavior; an in-process DLQ adapter/fake is sufficient (INTEGRATION-BRAKE a=no). Correctness does not depend on AI output (b=no) and has no multi-agent chain (c=no). Rejected higher level: System is disqualified by behavior text focusing on rejection + row number contract, not transport/runtime faults.","test_description":"Wire parser + schema validator + DLQ publisher adapter in-process. Feed CSV rows with missing required fields and assert DLQ records include the exact original row number and original row content; assert rows are not sent to normalized output.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The transformation correctly converts date strings in multiple formats (ISO 8601, US, European) to a single canonical format.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This behavior is pure transformation/parsing logic on one function/object boundary with no required I/O. The real failure is incorrect parsing/normalization rules, which unit tests catch directly. Rejected higher levels: Integration/System are disqualified because behavior text only specifies format conversion correctness, not cross-module or infrastructure effects; Agentic/Workflow disqualified because no AI dependency.","test_description":"Call the date-normalization function with representative ISO 8601, US (MM/DD/YYYY), and European (DD/MM/YYYY) inputs (including edge dates/ambiguities) and assert exact canonical output or explicit validation failure where ambiguous.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"A CSV file with 500,000 rows completes processing within the configured timeout without running out of memory.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Failure artifact is environment/runtime dependent: memory growth, GC behavior, wall-clock timeout, and process limits under large-volume execution (REAL-INFRA). In-process mocks can hide real throughput and memory pressure (MOCK-HIDE). Rejected lower level: Integration is insufficient because behavior explicitly requires timeout and memory guarantees at runtime scale, which need real process/OS observation.","test_description":"Run the pipeline as a real process on a generated 500k-row CSV with production-like config, enforce the configured timeout, and monitor peak RSS/exit status. Assert completion before timeout and no OOM/kill.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.13,"System":0.82,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When the S3 bucket returns a transient 503 error, the pipeline retries with exponential backoff rather than failing the entire batch.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Core failure is retry-policy wiring between S3 client wrapper, backoff policy, and batch controller (module boundary). This can be caught with deterministic stubbed S3 responses (503 then success) and clock/backoff assertions; real network is not required for this specific behavior (INTEGRATION-BRAKE a=no). No AI dependence (b=no) and no multi-agent chain (c=no). Rejected higher level: System is disqualified because behavior text targets retry logic on a known status code, not network stack variability.","test_description":"Compose pipeline modules with a fake S3 client scripted to return 503 for first N attempts then success. Assert retry count, increasing backoff delays, and that batch processing continues to completion instead of terminal failure.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.17,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Rows successfully written to PostgreSQL are not duplicated if the pipeline is restarted mid-batch.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Behavior depends on restart semantics across process lifecycles plus durable state coordination (checkpoint/offset vs committed DB rows). Real failure often appears only when a process is interrupted and restarted, which is subprocess/OS behavior (REAL-INFRA). Integration without real restart can miss ordering and commit-boundary bugs (MOCK-HIDE). Rejected lower level: Integration is disqualified by explicit behavior text 'restarted mid-batch,' which requires restart boundary validation.","test_description":"Execute pipeline against real PostgreSQL, force termination mid-batch after a known commit point, restart pipeline with same input, then assert final table has exactly one copy per logical row (idempotency/unique-key verification) and batch resumes from correct point.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.24,"System":0.68,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}}]}
